  <title>
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">Establish and Improve Water, Sanitation and Hygiene Services for Refugees &amp; Migrants in Lesvos RIC</narrative>
  </title>
  <description>
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">Greece has been experiencing significant migratory flows since 2015, which has resulted in an exponential increase in its migrant population in addition to a cumulating burden on its reception system. There are currently 121,000 migrants in Greece, including an estimated 44,500 children. This strain on the reception system has affected the capacity of the Greek government to adequately respond to the emergency needs of the migrant population, particularly on the islands &#x2013; one of the two entry points into the country and wider EU. While the number of arrivals in Greece during 2020 compared to previous years has decreased, the situation on the islands has not improved. In light of the overwhelming needs in Lesvos, IOM will cooperate with UNICEF to support the Government of Greece in its efforts to provide appropriate water, sanitation and hygiene services to the migrant population residing in the Reception and Identification Centre (RIC) established on the island of Lesvos.</narrative>
  </description>
